<br>
Well and truly, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;If I had root, I would walk as a God among men.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Kardaz:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  Talking about burden of proof. Where is the proof that root would makes us overpowered?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'm sorry.  I'm not the ones proposing a <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>change</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
It's not <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>my</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> job to prove it's unneeded, it's <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>your</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> job to prove it <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>is</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> needed.<br>
Likewise, it's not <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>my</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> job to prove that it is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>not</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> overpowering, rather it is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>your</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> job to prove that is <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>isn't</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.<br>
<br>
Lack of root has been a linchpin of mage class balance from the very beginning.  There had better be a very good reason to remove that linchpin, and frankly I don't see even a glimmer of it here.  Even if you concede the need for an escape spell, there are many alternatives that have far less impact on other areas of the game than root.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;I need an escape spell, therefore I need root&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is not a very formidable argument.<br>
<br>
Root is not simply an escape spell.  Its popular name is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;ghetto mezz&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and for good reason.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;I need an escape spell, therefore I need a generic but highly effective crowd control spell&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is an extraordinarily strong proposition, especially as mages have never had such a thing, and that fact has been considered a major balancing factor for mages since they were created.<br>
<br>
No, the burden of proof is on the advocates of change.  And extraordinary change demands extraordinary arguments.<br>
<br>
